Wk16 Pathology of the acute abdomen

6:18 PM 

Briefly describe the general mechanisms that can cause acute conditions of the abdomen (inflammatory, obstructive, vascular and traumatic) 

-Inflammatory due to infection or autoimmune cause 

-Obstructive - fecolith is stuck in bowel folds 

-Perforation - leading to peritonitis 

-Vascular/infarction - leading to swollen bowels 

-Metabolic - eg uremia, diabetic ketoacidosis, hypercalcemia  

-Cancer 

-Trauma 

 

Refer to PBL book for list of pathologies 

 

Briefly describe the abdominal structures that are pain sensitive and the stimuli that can induce pain in them 

Parietal pleura is sensitive to pain (somatic), whilst the visceral pleura is insensitive, with poorly localised pain. The visceral peritoneum is only sensitive to stretch, inflammation and ischemia. Pain from the visceral peritoneum is referred to areas of skin which are supplied by the same sensory ganglia and spinal cord segments as the nerve fibers innervating the viscera.  

 

Note that the abdominal prevertebral ganglia (sympathetic trunk) play an important role in pain perception. 

 

The enteric nervous system is also capable of detecting pain, originating at the submucosal plexus. 

 

 

Define peritonitis and briefly describe the common mechanisms that lead to it 

Peritonitis is inflammation of the peritoneum. It is caused by a rupture or perforation, which leads to leakage of contents into the peritoneal cavity. The immune response results in inflammation and hence peritonitis. 

 

The peritoneal cavity is lined by the single cell layer of mesothelium. The mesothelial cells compose the peritoneum.  

Causes: 

-Leakage of bile or pancreatic enzymes (sterile peritonitis) 

-Perforation or rupture of biliary system or bowel wall: may be complicated by bacterial infection 

-Foreign material causing fibrosis and inflammation 

-Perforation of abdominal viscera eg due to trauma 

 

Peritonitis = constant abdominal pain, life threatening due to impaired GIT motility and electrolyte balance. Bacterial spread to lungs is a dangerous possibility. 

 

Spontaneous peritonitis: involves bacterial infection, seen with liver or renal failure causing ascites (fluid in peritoneum) 

Secondary peritonitis: infection spread from GIT 

Retroperitonitis: bacterial infection in the retroperitoneal space, focusing on kidneys, bladder, adrenal glands, abdominal aorta (Note: sclerosing retroperitonitis involves dense retroperitoneal fibrosis frequently encompassing ureters to cause hydronephrosis) 

 

Briefly describe the possible consequences of infection and/or manipulation of the peritoneum 

Manipulation of the peritoneum can impair the motor function of the GI tract through disruption of the enteric nervous system.  

 

Define abscess and briefly describe the process of abscess formation 

An abscess is a collection of pus. Foreign organisms or material causes necrosis of subcutaneous tissue to produce an abscess cavity, which becomes filled with debris, bacteria, white blood cells and blood components. The wall of the abscess is made up of dermis infiltrated by inflammatory cells, surrounded by a fibrinous capsule.
